iplomacy that ended the Suez Crisis and earned Pearson the Nobel Peace Prize in 1957. Two appendices, taken from his diaries, show him hard at work at the United Nations during the Korean crisis.Mike captures Pearson’s intellect, his sense of humour, and his humanity, offering an inside look at the moments that shaped the twentieth century. This new edition features a foreword by Pearson cabinet minister and former prime minister Jean Chrétien.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPrime ministerszCanadavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aChretien, Rt. Hon. Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266865240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442668652423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442668652/original  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles